On Wednesday, Islamabad denied violating the ceasefire in Kashmir, a flashpoint for Indian-Pakistani conflicts.
Indian officials accused Pakistan of firing mortars across the border, causing injuries.
The two countries planned to discuss the incident.
Meanwhile, India's Prime Minister announced the resumption of a bus service between the divided zones of Kashmir, a positive outcome of ongoing dialogue.
Despite tensions, Kashmiris on both sides expressed joy at the prospect of reuniting after decades of separation.
The bus service symbolizes a step towards peace in the region, amidst ongoing talks and gestures of goodwill.
